  <info><![CDATA[# Church Polarization Agent-Based Model
Eric Araújo, Katelin Jandris, Ryan Klein, Övgü Tufan


## Model Vision
This agent-based model project aims to illuminate the underlying mechanisms that drive such polarization and identify opportunities for strengthening unity within faith communities. Specifically, we are interested in the conditions under which diversity within a church community remains stable. Are there conditions in which declining perceived fit leads to nonlinear levels of polarization? It’s important to note that rather than offering prescriptive solutions, we aim to empower church leaders with insights that help them navigate these challenges with wisdom and care. We recognize the limitations of such a model: it cannot fully capture the richness of individual faith journeys, the role of theology, or the complexity of spiritual life. It is also constrained by the assumptions we embed in the model and the data available to us. However, by visualizing the invisible social dynamics that often go unnoticed, we hope to offer a valuable tool for reflection and conversation.

## Framework
To structure our model, we adopt a trifold framework that integrates three key dimensions:
  1. Beliefs: This dimension captures the political and religious beliefs of the agents. We represent political beliefs on a continuous spectrum (e.g., from left to right) and religious beliefs as a measure of commitment or orthodoxy.
  2. Sense of Belonging: This dimension reflects how connected agents feel to the church community. It is influenced by the similarity of their beliefs to those of other members and their level of participation in church activities.
  3. Behavior: This dimension encompasses the actions of the agents, such as attending church services, participating in church events, and engaging with other members. Behavior is influenced by both beliefs and sense of belonging, creatin a feedback loop where participation can reinforce or weaken an agent’sconnection to the community.

### Time Steps
Each time step represents one week, during which agents can attend church services, interact with peers, and update their beliefs and sense of belonging.

## Interface Parameters
num_members Number of agents in the church community
polarization-degree: the degree of initial polarization
epsilon-p: Political boundedconfidence threshold
epsilon-r: Religious boundedconfidence threshold
mu-p: Political peer influence rate
mu-r: Religious peer influence rate
lambda-p: External political influence weight
lamda-r: External religious influence weight
alpha: Belonging gain rate (belief alignment)
beta: Belonging loss rate (belief divergence)
phi: Attendance bonus
rho: Passive decay rate (nonattendance)
p-weight: Political weight in combined factor
theta-min: Absolute belonging floor
gamma: Weight of belonging vs. belief alignment in participation
delta: Disengagement observation threshold
ext-p: the ambient political environment outside the congregation
ext-r: the ambient religious environment outside the congregation
Note that beta > alpha and ρ < beta must hold for the model to behave as intended

## Citations

Small World Network Extension:
Wilensky, U. (2015). NetLogo Small Worlds model. http://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/models/SmallWorlds. Center for Connected Learning and Computer-Based Modeling, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL.

Wilensky, U. (1999). NetLogo. http://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/. Center for Connected Learning and Computer-Based Modeling, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL.]]></info>
